To own Exxon today, you need to believe its integrated “megamajor” model and advantaged assets in the Permian, Guyana and LNG can keep generating solid cash returns while it gradually builds out lower carbon businesses. The latest earnings beat and confirmation of hefty buybacks reinforce that near term capital returns are still a central catalyst. The more immediate risk now is not operational, but governance related, as shareholder pushback on redomiciling to Texas puts Exxon under fresh scrutiny.
The exempt solicitation from the New York City Police Pension Fund is therefore important, because it puts Exxon's new retail voting program and proposed move to Texas directly in front of investors just weeks after the company highlighted record production and US$9.2 billion of Q1 shareholder distributions. How this governance debate plays out may influence how much credit investors give those operational and capital return catalysts in the short term.
